<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-simple-inequalities" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Simple Inequalities</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.3 Linear Inequalities
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Solve compound inequalities in one unknown
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on activity -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        5 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To re-introduce simple inequalities through a real life problem
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                    <p>
                        Guide learners to using the <m>\le</m> symbol and solve the equation.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of 3 or 4 learners
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Materials needed:</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A notebook or a sheet of paper
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A pen or pencil
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Instructions:</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                In your groups discuss the following problem
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            On a market day you are sent to the local market with Ksh. <m>500</m>. You are instructed to buy a packet of maize flour (unga) which costs Ksh <m>230</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            With the remaining money, you want to buy as many bananas as possible. Each banana costs Ksh. <m>50</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Will you be able to buy <m>6</m> bananas? Discuss with your group why or why not.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
            <p>
                Since you cannot spend more than the Ksh. <m>500</m> you have, use an inequality symbol (<m>\lt</m>, <m>\gt</m>, <m>\le</m>, or <m>\ge</m>) to connect your total cost expression to your budget of Ksh. <m>500</m>.
            </p>
        </hint>
        <solution component="lesson-plan">
            <p>
                The total cost is <m>230 + 50b</m>, where <m>b</m> represents the number of bananas. Since you cannot spend more than Ksh. <m>500</m>, we have:
                <md>
                    <mrow>230 + 50b \amp \le 500 </mrow>
                    <mrow>50 b \amp \le 270</mrow>
                    <mrow>b \amp \le 5.4 </mrow>
                </md>
                Since you cannot buy a fraction of a banana, the maximum number of bananas you can buy is <m>5</m>. Therefore, you will not be able to buy <m>6</m> bananas.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </activity>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on structured lesson plan-->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the concepts and properties learners discovered in the Learner Experience.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Remind learners of the key properties of inequalities and how to solve them, including the rule about flipping the inequality sign when multiplying or dividing by a negative number.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <p>
            Inequalities allow us to compare quantities. We use these four symbols:
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title><m>\gt</m></title>
                    <p>
                        greater than
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title><m>\ge</m></title>
                    <p>
                        greater than or equal to
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title><m>\lt</m></title>
                    <p>
                        less than
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title><m>\le</m></title>
                    <p>
                        less than or equal to
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <p>
            We solve inequalities by performing the same operations on both sides of the inequality, just like we do with equations.
        </p>
        <p>
            However, remember that whenever you multiply or divide both sides of an inequality by a negative number, the inequality sign must reverse (flip) its direction, so less than becomes greater than.
        </p>
        <p>
            For instance, if <m>-x \lt 5</m>, dividing by <m>-1</m> results in <m>x \gt -5</m>.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the inequality <m>15 - 2x \ge 7</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                First you subtract <m>15</m> from both sides to group the constants:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>2x \amp \ge 7 - 15</mrow>
                    <mrow>2x \amp \ge -8 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Then we divide both sides by <m>-2</m>. Since we are dividing by a negative number, we must flip the inequality symbol from <m>\ge</m> to <m>\le</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>x \amp \le \frac{-8}{-2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x \amp \le 4</mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the following inequality:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>3x - 9 \amp \lt 6 + x</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                First, we group the variable terms on one side and the constants on the other side. We can do this by subtracting <m>x</m> from both sides and adding <m>9</m> to both sides:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>3x - x \amp \lt 6 + 9</mrow>
                    <mrow>2x \amp \lt 15</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Then we divide both sides by <m>2</m> to solve for <m>x</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>x \amp \lt \frac{15}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x \amp \lt 7.5</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <em>Shireri</em> Primary School has a handwashing water tank that currently holds <m>80</m> litres of water. The tap has a slight leak and loses water at a rate of <m>4</m> litres every hour. The school security guard wants to ensure there are always strictly more than <m>20</m> litres left in the tank for the afternoon classes.
            </p>
            <p>
                If <m>h</m> represents the number of hours the tank has been leaking, write an inequality for this situation and solve for <m>h</m> to find out how many hours the water will remain above the <m>20</m>-litre mark.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                We can start by writing an expression for the amount of water left in the tank after <m>h</m> hours. Since the tank loses <m>4</m> litres every hour, the amount of water lost after <m>h</m> hours is <m>4h</m>. Therefore, the amount of water left in the tank after <m>h</m> hours can be expressed as:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Water left} \amp = 80 - 4h </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The security guard wants to ensure that there are always more than <m>20</m> litres left, so we can set up the inequality:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> 80 - 4h \amp \gt 20</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Next, we solve for <m>h</m>. First, we subtract <m>80</m> from both sides:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>-4h \amp \gt 20 - 80 </mrow>
                    <mrow>-4h \amp \gt -60</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Then we divide both sides by <m>-4</m>. Since we are dividing by a negative number, we must flip the inequality symbol from <m>\gt</m> to <m>\lt</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>h \amp \lt \frac{-60}{-4}</mrow>
                    <mrow>h \amp \lt 15</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the water will remain above the <m>20</m>-litre mark for less than <m>15</m> hours.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- If STACK questions are included, uncomment this: -->

    <!-- <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/checkpoint.ptx" /> -->

    <!-- Add STACK exercises if made -->

    <!-- Add static exercises -->

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Solve the inequality <m>2x - 5 \le 9</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>x \le 7</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A <em>matatu</em> is licensed to carry a maximum of <m>14</m> passengers. If <m>p</m> represents the number of passengers currently in the <em>matatu</em>, write a simple inequality to represent the legal number of passengers it can carry.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>p \le 14</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>4x - 9 \ge 11</m>. What is the smallest integer value of <m>x</m> that makes this inequality true?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>x \ge 5</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <em>Wanjiku</em>, a Grade <m>11</m> student, was asked to solve the inequality <m>-3x + 4 \gt 19</m>. She showed her working as follows:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>-3x \amp \gt 19 - 4</mrow>
                        <mrow>-3x \amp \gt 15</mrow>
                        <mrow>x \amp \gt \frac{15}{-3}</mrow>
                        <mrow>x \amp \gt -5</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Is <em>Wanjiku's</em> solution correct? If not, identify the error and provide the correct solution.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <em>Wanjiku's</em> solution is incorrect.
                </p>
                 <p>
                    The error occurs in the step where she divides both sides of the inequality by <m>-3</m>. Since she is dividing by a negative number, she should have flipped the inequality symbol from <m>\gt</m> to <m>\lt</m>. The correct solution is:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>x \lt -5</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <em>Mwakidize</em>, a local poultry farmer has a total budget of Ksh. <m>3,000</m> to buy chick mash. Transporting the feed to the farm costs a flat rate of Ksh <m>300</m> regardless of the amount bought. If each bag of chick mash costs Ksh <m>650</m>, write and solve an inequality to determine the maximum number of bags the farmer can buy. Explain why your final mathematical answer must be a whole number in this real-life situation.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    When <m>n</m> represent the number of bags of chick mash.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>n \le 4.15</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Since the number of bags must be a whole number, the maximum number of bags the farmer can buy is <m>4</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Mike says the following are all true statements:
                    <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>a + b \lt a - b</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>2\sqrt{ab} \le a + b </m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>-a \le a </m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>a \ge \frac{1}{a}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                    Explain which statements are true, and provide a counterexample for any statement that is false.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                This statement is false. A counterexample is when <m>a = 5</m> and <m>b = 2</m>, which gives us <m>7 \lt 3</m>, which is not true.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                This statement is true (for non-negative <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>). We can prove it by noticing that squares are always positive, so:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>0 \amp \le \left(\sqrt{a} - \sqrt{b}\right)^2 </mrow>
                                    <mrow>0 \amp \le a - 2\sqrt{ab} + b </mrow>
                                    <mrow>2\sqrt{ab} \amp \le a + b </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                This statement is true for non-negative <m>a</m>. However, if <m>a</m> is negative, the statement is false. For example, if <m>a = -3</m>, then <m>-a = 3</m>, which is not less than or equal to <m>-3</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                This statement is false. A counterexample is when <m>a = 0.5</m>, which gives us <m>0.5 \ge 2</m>, which is not true.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Consider the triangle shown below with side lengths <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m>.
                </p>
                <figure>
                    <caption>Triangle with side lengths <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <shortdescription>A triangle with three sides labeled a, b, and c.</shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
                                \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                                \coordinate (B) at (4,0);
                                \coordinate (C) at (1.2,2.5);
                                \draw (A)--(B) node[midway, below] {$c$};
                                \draw (B)--(C) node[midway, right] {$a$};
                                \draw (C)--(A) node[midway, left] {$b$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                <p>
                    The triangle inequality theorem tells us that:
                </p>
                <theorem xml:id="thm-triangle-ineq">
                    <title>The Triangle Inequality</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            The sum of the lengths of any two sides of a triangle must be greater than the length of the third side
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                </theorem>
                <p>
                    Translate this statement into three mathematical inequalities using the side lengths <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>a + b \gt c</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>a + c \gt b</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>b + c \gt a</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In this exercise, you will verify the triangle inequality theorem by constructing and measuring your own triangle.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Draw a triangle of any shape and size on a sheet of paper. Label the three sides as <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Use a ruler to measure each side length in centimetres. Record your measurements.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                For each pair of sides, add their lengths and verify that the sum is greater than the third side. Record your results in the following format:
                            </p>
                            <tabular>
                                <row header="yes">
                                    <cell>Sum of two sides</cell>
                                    <cell>Third side</cell>
                                    <cell>Is the sum greater than the third side?</cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell>?</cell>
                                    <cell>?</cell>
                                    <cell>?</cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell>?</cell>
                                    <cell>?</cell>
                                    <cell>?</cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell>?</cell>
                                    <cell>?</cell>
                                    <cell>?</cell>
                                </row>
                            </tabular>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Based on your measurements, does the triangle inequality theorem hold for your triangle? Explain your findings.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    This is a practical exercise where learners verify the triangle inequality theorem using their own measurements. Answers will vary depending on the triangle drawn and measurements taken.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The key finding should be that for the triangle drawn, all three inequalities hold:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>a + b \gt c</m>, <m>a + c \gt b</m>, and <m>b + c \gt a</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    This confirms that the triangle inequality theorem is true for their triangle.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

